About this item

  • Compatible with the following devices: Compatible with smart thermostats ( Nest, Ecobee, Honeywell, Sensi, Emerson, Hive, etc ) and doorbells ( Ring Video Doorbell, Ring Video Doorbell 2, Ring Video Doorbell Pro, Nest Skybell, Zmodo WiFi smart doorbell, Nest Hello doorbell, Eufy, Skybell, Arlo etc.) and other devices that require 24 volt power With constant power and constant operation
  • Product Parameters: Input AC 120V, 60Hz 0.2A, output 24V / 500mA. Cable length is 315 inches / 8 meters.
  • Easy To Install: 2 pin non-polarity wires support easy and quick install, Assemble along the wall from your outlet to the doorbell and thermostat, 26 ft cable is long enough to plug it into an electrical outlet inside or outside your house.
  • Security: Special design and materials ensure that provide the best current output connected to your device. Prevent short circuit, overvoltage, overcurrent, overheat, ensure charging safety.
  • Please note: Please check whether your device is the model in the details before purchasing.

How customer reviews and ratings work

Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

  • Ziggy
    5.0 out of 5 stars Works for wiring Nest Thermostat
    Reviewed in the United States on December 11, 2022
    Verified Purchase
    I used this transformer to provide power to a single Nest Thermostat. The thermostat was wired for heat only (R and W wires) without a common. To wire this in, I first shutoff power to my boiler. At my thermostat, I then removed the R-wire coming from the boiler (tucked into the wall) and connected the two wires from this transformer to my R and C terminals, keeping the W-wire connected from the boiler. I then turned the boiler power back on, then configured my Nest Thermostat for R-W-C wiring. Everything has worked and the thermostat is no longer throwing codes for low power.

    This solution works best if you have an electric outlet near your thermostat or near the wall you're going to fish the wire up to the device.
